h, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lamarque","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Adrien, Andre, Jean-Francois, Jean-Louis, Maryse, Yolaine.  Spanish Ana, Arturo, Ezequiel, Francisco, Juan, Ramon, Ruben.","French: habitational name from Lamarque or La Marque, names of several places in various parts of France named with Old French <i>marque</i> (ancient Germanic <i>marca</i>) ‘frontier, border’. This surname is also found in Haiti and Mauritius."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilde de Lamarque was born in Lamarque, Hautes-Pyrénées, Midi-Pyrénées, France as the daughter of Garsion de L